<subSubSection lastPageId="24" lastPageNumber="25" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,1590,2013]" lastBlockId="24.[151,1437,151,393]" lastPageId="24" lastPageNumber="25" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1734,1760]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Comments</emphasis>
: this oligochaete was described as 
<taxonomicName authority="Michaelsen, 1900" authorityName="Michaelsen" authorityYear="1926" box="[719,928,1735,1761]" class="Clitellata" family="Naididae" genus="Schmardaella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplotaxida" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="lutzi">
<emphasis box="[719,928,1735,1761]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Schmardaella lutzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Michaelsen, W." box="[970,1180,1735,1762]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="231 - 235" refId="ref24363" refString="Michaelsen, W. (1926) Schmardaella lutzi Mich., oligochaeto endoparasitico de Hylidas sul-Americans. Memorias do Instituto Oswaldo Cruz, 19, 231 - 235. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / S 0074 - 02761926000200004" type="journal article" year="1926">Michaelsen (1926)</bibRefCitation>
and after the subgenus 
<taxonomicName box="[151,248,1771,1797]" class="Clitellata" family="Naididae" genus="Allodero" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplotaxida" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,248,1771,1797]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Allodero</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was erected by 
<bibRefCitation author="Sperber, C." box="[431,600,1771,1797]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="1 - 296" refId="ref26813" refString="Sperber, C. (1948) A taxonomical study of the Naididae. Zoologiska Bidrag Fran Uppsala, 28, 1 - 296." type="journal article" year="1948">Sperber (1948)</bibRefCitation>
in the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[752,809,1771,1796]" class="Clitellata" family="Randiellidae" genus="Dero" kingdom="Animalia" order="Enchytraeida" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[752,809,1771,1796]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Dero</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for parasitic and symbiotic species. There are some debates on the nature of the relationship between anurans and 
<taxonomicName authority="" box="[833,1014,1807,1833]" class="Clitellata" family="Randiellidae" genus="Dero" kingdom="Animalia" order="Enchytraeida" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Annelida" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Allodero">
<emphasis box="[833,1014,1807,1833]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Dero (Allodero)</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. (
<emphasis box="[1085,1119,1807,1832]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">e.g</emphasis>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Lutz, A." box="[1134,1253,1807,1833]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="485 - 486" refId="ref23784" refString="Lutz, A. (1927) Sur la Schmardaella lutzi Michaelsen. Comptes rendus des seances de la Societe de biologie, 96, 485 - 486." type="journal article" year="1927">Lutz 1927</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Harman, W. J." box="[1266,1424,1807,1833]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="225 - 228" refId="ref22794" refString="Harman, W. J. (1971) A review of the subgenus Allodero (Oligochaeta: Naididae: Dero) with a description of D. (A.) floridana n. sp. from Bufo terrestris. Transactions of the American Microscopical Society, 90 (2), 225 - 228. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 3225029" type="journal article" year="1971">Harman 1971</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Andrews, J. M. &amp; Childress, J. N. &amp; Iakovidis, T. J. &amp; Langford, G. J." box="[151,397,1842,1869]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="275 - 281" refId="ref18237" refString="Andrews, J. M., Childress, J. N., Iakovidis, T. J. &amp; Langford, G. J. (2015) Elucidating the life history and ecological aspects of Allodero hylae (Annelida: Clitellata: Naididae): a parasitic oligochaete of invasive Cuban tree frogs in Florida. Journal of Parasitology, 101, 275 - 281. https: // doi. org / 10.1645 / 14 - 608.1" type="journal article" year="2015">
Andrews 
<emphasis box="[259,309,1843,1869]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">et al</emphasis>
. (2015)
</bibRefCitation>
integrating field data and laboratory experiments with tree frogs confirmed a free-living and a parasitic stage of 
<taxonomicName authority="Goodchild. These" authorityName="Goodchild. These" box="[365,815,1879,1905]" class="Clitellata" family="Randiellidae" genus="Dero" kingdom="Animalia" order="Enchytraeida" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="hylae" subGenus="Allodero">
<emphasis box="[365,611,1879,1905]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Dero (Allodero) hylae</emphasis>
Goodchild. These
</taxonomicName>
authors did not find oligochaetes in breeding pounds of hylids but found free-living stages in nearby bromealid tanks. In this way, the aquatic environment of bromealids provides a way for oligochaetes to infect hylids by cloaca and then reach ureters and kidneys (
<bibRefCitation author="Andrews, J. M. &amp; Childress, J. N. &amp; Iakovidis, T. J. &amp; Langford, G. J." box="[1193,1425,1950,1977]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="275 - 281" refId="ref18237" refString="Andrews, J. M., Childress, J. N., Iakovidis, T. J. &amp; Langford, G. J. (2015) Elucidating the life history and ecological aspects of Allodero hylae (Annelida: Clitellata: Naididae): a parasitic oligochaete of invasive Cuban tree frogs in Florida. Journal of Parasitology, 101, 275 - 281. https: // doi. org / 10.1645 / 14 - 608.1" type="journal article" year="2015">
Andrews 
<emphasis box="[1302,1351,1951,1977]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">et al</emphasis>
. 2015
</bibRefCitation>
). Our specimens of 
<taxonomicName authority="Michaelsen, 1900" authorityName="Michaelsen" authorityYear="1926" box="[352,481,1987,2013]" class="Clitellata" family="Naididae" genus="Schmardaella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplotaxida" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="lutzi" subGenus="Allodero">
<emphasis box="[352,379,1987,2012]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">D.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[394,418,1987,2013]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">A.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[433,481,1987,2013]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">lutzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are segmented and do not present reproductive organs; body segments have forked se- tae only in ventral region, and these worms lack branchial fossa and gills; when alive they are red and when fixed are white (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Michaelsen, W." box="[273,466,187,213]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" pagination="231 - 235" refId="ref24363" refString="Michaelsen, W. (1926) Schmardaella lutzi Mich., oligochaeto endoparasitico de Hylidas sul-Americans. Memorias do Instituto Oswaldo Cruz, 19, 231 - 235. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / S 0074 - 02761926000200004" type="journal article" year="1926">Michaelsen 1926</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Oda, F. H. &amp; Petsch, D. K. &amp; Ragonha, F. H. &amp; Batista, V. G. &amp; Takeda, A. M. &amp; Takemoto, R. M." box="[521,700,186,213]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" pagination="86 - 90" refId="ref24964" refString="Oda, F. H., Petsch, D. K., Ragonha, F. H., Batista, V. G., Takeda, A. M. &amp; Takemoto, R. M. (2015) Dero (Allodero) lutzi Michaelsen, 1926 (Oligochaeta: Naididae) associated with Scinax fuscovarius Lutz, 1925 (Anura: Hylidae) from semi-deciduous Atlantic Rain Forest, Southern Brazil. Brazilian Journal of Biology, 75, 86 - 90. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / 1519 - 6984.07613" type="journal article" year="2015">
Oda 
<emphasis box="[575,624,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">et al</emphasis>
. 2015
</bibRefCitation>
). These features are changed in free-living stages; for this reason, 
<bibRefCitation author="Andrews, J. M. &amp; Childress, J. N. &amp; Iakovidis, T. J. &amp; Langford, G. J." box="[151,401,222,249]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" pagination="275 - 281" refId="ref18237" refString="Andrews, J. M., Childress, J. N., Iakovidis, T. J. &amp; Langford, G. J. (2015) Elucidating the life history and ecological aspects of Allodero hylae (Annelida: Clitellata: Naididae): a parasitic oligochaete of invasive Cuban tree frogs in Florida. Journal of Parasitology, 101, 275 - 281. https: // doi. org / 10.1645 / 14 - 608.1" type="journal article" year="2015">
Andrews 
<emphasis box="[261,311,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">et al</emphasis>
. (2015)
</bibRefCitation>
mentioned that the free-living stage of 
<taxonomicName box="[852,1000,223,249]" class="Clitellata" family="Randiellidae" genus="Dero" kingdom="Animalia" order="Enchytraeida" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="hylae" subGenus="Allodero">
<emphasis box="[852,1000,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">D. (A.) hylae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
could be confounded by non-parasitic species of 
<taxonomicName box="[271,328,259,284]" class="Clitellata" family="Randiellidae" genus="Dero" kingdom="Animalia" order="Enchytraeida" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[271,328,259,284]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Dero</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
pointing out the importance to collect oligochaetes from the tree frogs for parasitological studies. From the 18 anuran species reported with 
<taxonomicName authority="Michaelsen, 1900" authorityName="Michaelsen" authorityYear="1926" box="[617,747,295,321]" class="Clitellata" family="Naididae" genus="Schmardaella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplotaxida" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="lutzi" subGenus="Allodero">
<emphasis box="[617,747,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">D. (A.) lutzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in South America (
<collectingCountry box="[962,1032,295,321]" name="Brazil" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Brazil</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1084,1204,295,322]" name="Venezuela" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
), only one is bufonid while the others are hylids (Morais 
<emphasis box="[549,599,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">et al</emphasis>
. 2017).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1437,151,393]" box="[199,912,367,393]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">**This data has already been published by Morais et al. (2017).</paragraph>
